deck_excerpt: Offer a silent prayer (and steal stuff) with Kashtira Voiceless Voice!
deck_description:
Voiceless Voice is a very potent deck in the specific space of Master Duel's format. It plays well into Maxx 'C', liberal space for non-engine to pack outs to problem board states, enough power and resillience to deal with opponents' attempts to kill you, and has ways around most common handtraps (except Gamma, but that bozo's functionally leaving the format in a week so even that won't be a problem). While Yubel and Tenpai are presently superior decks, Voiceless Voice stands as one of their unsung rivals.

The only question was how you wanted to build the deck. Branded and Dogmatika were common choices in the TCG, but Branded's limits in MD make that a non-starter IMO and Dogmatika just doesn't have the punch I'm looking for. Pure VV was, of course, an option (and how I played it in the past, I have a deck profile for pure from a few months ago).

Then I encountered the concept of Kashtira Voiceless Voice. I forget what gave me this idea, whether it was running into it in Ranked or seeing a decklist on YGOPRO or even just thinking about Kashtira Snake-Eyes (for those who remember that innovation from the MD playerbase), but here it is. I won't go into the card-by-card, but here's some reasoning on why I've built it this way:

  • Kashtira is an engine that can be played before starting your main VV line without any issue. Drawing Unicorn or Wraitsoth is full Kash combo, and both baits out handtraps and disincentivizes your opponent from handtrapping the VV line by way of Unicorn's presence. It can also be performed without running into Nibiru by pausing your Kashtira combo after Unicorn's search, running through the VV line from there, then continuing after Skull Guardian's negate is online. It also means you're less likely to brick on non-engine, since three Kashtira cards are straight one-card combos and there's some two card combos that can all result in Shangri+Ariseheart on field even if you don't draw a VV card.
  • In a similar vein, the Kashtiras are also a good source of tribute fodder for the VV Rituals. They're all level 7 (except Riseheart, but he can even make himself a 7 if you're truly desperate), meaning you can use them as the whole material when summoning with Saffira's GY effect. Note that not being LIGHT means they cannot be used for a Ritual Summon with Prayers, however.
  • Kashtira also functions as a strong extra end-board set-up. Ariseheart is a walking Macros Cosmos with a huge attack stat and removal (and under Barrier, cannot be targeted for attack while Lo+Skull Guardian are present), which means he can often shut down turns on his own.
  • On the other end, Voiceless Voice is able to tolerate Ariseheart's presence as an end-board piece as long as you're not an idiot. Blessing lets you recur banished cards, and as long as you don't tribute Lo while Ariseheart's on the field you can generally get away with having him there.
  • Tenpai also has a decent amount of difficulty playing through Voiceless Voice if you can get Sauravis, Ancient and Ascended onto the field. While they theoretically have ways around it, a lot of Tenpai players will run straight into Sauravis by summoning Bident (at which point you can just use Sauravis to banish it before it even technically hits the field, removing it from being a problem at all). Prayers also lets us swiftly recover from most of Tenpai's destruction-based board-breakers, summoning Skull Guardian then reviving Lo to turn the negate back online.
  • We also main-deck 2x Evenly Matched as our primary board-breaker. It's half-economic purposes (Evenly is the best SR rarity board-breaker), but also that I find it preferable in most match-ups over other options. It's especially strong into Yubel, who is probably the best going-first deck in the format right now.
  • Imperm is probably the hand-trap I fear most right now, on grounds that it dodges Triple Tactics Talent and Called By (two of the anti-handtrap tools we run), meaning we need to hard-open Sauravis to fully be safe on protecting our activations.
  • Extra Deck is definitely very flexible. I rarely ever actually use any of these cards outside of the Kashtira line, so feel free to experiment.
  • Droll & Lock Bird is very bad if it is activated on our turn, but it also is not especially common in this format right now. We can manage if we hard-open Lo+Skull Guardian, but otherwise you will have to figure out a line on your own based on your hand. There's not a lot of good options, sadly.

deck_name: Locals: Tistina FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14 players [ROTA Celebration Event] [30.11.2024]
deck_excerpt: Locals: Tistina FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14 players [ROTA Celebration Event] [30.11.2024]
deck_description:
Round 1 vs Sharks ( 2 - 1 )

Round 2 vs Fiendsmith Azamina Snake-Eyes ( 2 - 1 )

Round 3 vs Runick Branded Bystial Synchro ( 2 - 0 )

Round 4 vs Bystial Centurion ( 2 - 1 )

 

Engine is pretty much set in stone for me. Terrortop is crazy because he sets up more combos using Levirtue Dragon and helps playing through handtraps using Totembird or Gossip Shadow. I dont main Virtue Stream though because you mostly just make Levirtue Dragon when you draw terrortop while Silhouhatte Rabbit can always be made and works under droll, playing both is too many bricks.

Non-engine was nice, would probably run more handtraps instead of Fenrir though. Daruma Cannon was busted again, even going second it just forces a grindgame which this deck mostly wins.

played 42 because I felt like with 40 you draw too many duplicates. With my next lists I will stay at 42 - 44.

Nothing too special in the extra deck. 2 Varudras is mandatory, I play 3 just in case. Lyna sadly didnt come up, but dont know if I would swap her for Knightmare Phoenix again. Lyna is nice if you want to make S:P and can search Demigod if you crash with her.

In the side deck, im honestly just trying out some things. I always play Ultimate Slayer + Targets, Thrust, Talents, Duster and now Dbarrier too. I also side Virtue Stream for going first.

I sided Phantazmay but never found him, same with Cosmic Cyclone. They could theoretically have been pretty good still so I dont know if I will keep them in the side deck or not.

 

Overall Im extremely happy with that list. The only things you could maybe improve is playing a small fiendsmith engine, but I havent tried that yet and it might not even be the right decision because of how many extra deck slots it requires.
Based Tenpai

deck_excerpt: Infinitrack aiming to Special Summon Arise-Heart.
deck_description:
The main goal of the deck is to SS Arise-Heart through Outrigger Extension. There is several road to do that. The only one card access to Arise-Heart is using the SHS engine but it can do so much better things in this deck. I give after this some combo lines often used. The end board is usually composed of an Arise-Heart supported by Outrigger Extension and Infinitrack Road Roller , a Cyber Dragon Infinity and either a S:P Little Knight or a Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu" .

 

Infinitrack Combo : The main downside of the Infinitrack line is that it is not a one card combo. To perform the combo you need to have Infinitrack Harvester or Heavy Forward in the hand and to found a way to SS one Earth Machine on the field. I will assume here that I have already that Eart Machine monster on the field and will perform from there. I will give after that ways to access this monster.

- Normal Summon Harvester and activate its effect to add Road Roller to the hand.

- Link Summon the Ballista using Harvester and the Earth Machin already on the field.

- Activate Ballista effect to add Box and then Box effect to add Infinitrack Crab Crane to the hand.

- Activate Crane effect tributing Ballista to SS Crane.

- Activate Cran effect banishing Ballista to add Outrigger to the hand.

- The effect of Road trigger in the hand to SS itself.

- Activate Outrigger from the hand, portecting your Xyz from targeting.

- Summon Infinitrack River Stormer and then activate its effect detaching Crane to add whatever you want from hand. Usually the targets are either Superheavy Samurai Motorbike if you didn't use the SHS engine yet, or, if you already use it, a card for the follow-up like Pegasus or Anchor Drill. You can also send Trencher or Tunneler to the GY instead. Trencher allow to extend and Tunneler to draw.

- Activate Outrigger effect targeting River to SS Arise-Heart. You now have an Arise protected from targets and that is quite hard to pass through battle because of Road Roller's effect.

 

How to acces the Earth Machine monster ? Now to perform the previous combo you need one Earth Machine monster on the field. There is 3 ways to do it : Infinitrack Anchor Drill , Vernusylph of the Awakening Forests or the SHS engine. Those are my favorite but you can use other instead, like the trains. I found those quite usefull since Anchor is accessible through Heavy Forward, the Vernusylph can send a Road Roller to the GY to SS after and the SHS engine is so powerfull here.

 

The SHS combo : I come now to the SHS engine and all the versatility it gives to the deck. I recall here the basic SHS combo :

- Wakaushi -> Monk -> Soulgaia

You now have 2 LV4 on the field. One of them being an Earth Machine tuner. What can you do from there ?

- You can perform your previous combo, Soulgaia being the Earth Machine monster.

- You can Xyz Summon Gear Gigant X to add Harvester turning your SHS engine on a one card combor. You can also add something else to extend like another infinitrack.

- You can go into the Synchrol line. Synchro Bureido and activate its effect to SS Shirokunishi and place Wakaushi into the Pendulum zone. Synchro Bureibu and activate its effect to SS Kunamzan.

This last play is the most powerfull. The Kunamzan can be used as the Earth Machine monster from Infinitrack combo but it also provide a LV5 to go into Cyber Dragon Infinity. It also provide a Pendulum Summon that can help to extend either with Pegasus or Anchor Drill and can often give access to Infinity or S:P.

deck_excerpt: Crow Hogan's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the ARC-V era.
deck_description:
Blackwing Assault - Crow Hogan's deck updated. Trying to bring the best out of his character deck whilst keeping it in the ARC-V era so no Link monsters.

Let me know if you've got any ideas to improve it.

(This is a modified version of my original profile, which can be seen at https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/abc-xyz-ft-the-world-turbo-524971)

After a lot of testing and theorycrafting, I've been able to modify my original build into a much higher power ceiling, increasing its ability to build a heavily defensive board and enhance its grind game in the situations where you cannot perform the cheeky The World FTK without sacrificing the capability to perform said FTK. I even made a (terrible) video showing how this time!

First things first, the ability to perform The World FTK is a 1-card combo off of both Union Hangar (which includes Terraforming and Set Rotation) and Union Activation. The line is similar within both, as your goal is just to gather all six pieces of the A-to-Z fusions, get Light Barrier, and put Union Activation into the GY. Basically, this hasn't changed from the previous build.

A major change, however, is the expansion of the Fiendsmith engine to be more complete. The addition of Lacrima and Sanct in addition to Engraver is just to give the deck a bit more grind capability - you can summon Lacrima off of Requiem to pitch Engraver for the summon of Desirae and link Desirae and Sequence off for Agnumdei, and that will set you up for at least one revival of Desirae if it's outed at some point. Of course, this is all in the event you either decide you dont want to or are unable to position yourself to summon The World.

Speaking of "unable to summon The World", the backup endboard has been modified greatly, weaving both Psy-Framelord Omega and Silhouhatte Rabbit into the line to add both a hand rip and a summon negate in the form of Azurune.

All in all, these modifications make the deck feel much nicer - less chaff in the Extra Deck, every piece of the combo is actually used reasonably often, and the ability to FTK is not sacrificed in the process.

deck_excerpt: It is December 2024, and Runick remains the strongest Spright variant in Masterduel!
deck_description:
It is December 2024, nearly two years after Spright has been released, and Runick remains the strongest Spright variant in Masterduel! Don't believe me? Watch the video and play it for yourself!

The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from a last year.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_name: Yami Marik: Paleozoic / Winged Dragon of Ra (LOTD:LE)
deck_description:
This deck was made based on Winged Dragon of Ra, the Egyptian god.

This card's first owner was Marik Ishtar, a gravekeeper of Pharaoh's tomb whose was sucked by the darkness of the Millennium Rod, turning him into Yami Marik the "Rare Hunter".

As you know Legacy of the Duelist Link Evolution doesn't have the great support of Divine-Beasts nor the Ra itself. But Ra is an even stronger GOD than the other 2, because of the Sphere Mode.

In this deck you can make use of Sphere Mode but you can summon Ra even with normal tributing. There are many cards that let you summon multiple monsters while there are many cards to control the board with the help of paleozoics. "The first Monarch" can be treated as 2 monsters when tributed, to make the summoning easier. Most paleozoic decks exceed the 40 cards limit for consistency (to 60 cards main deck) by adding "Needlebug nest" and many other useless paleozoics. But this isn't just a Paleozoic deck, it's made for summoning Ra and we don't want to discard Ra cards randomly...

The idea came from the card "Metal Reflect Slime" which is a trap card treated as a monster. While "Mother Grizzly" can search "Deep Diver", which is able to search for every possible monster card, something that is so difficult for other cards (cause Ra and Slifer doesn't have ATK, they have ???? or even XXXX).

"Shining angel" can search for "Junk collector" and if you have "elemental burst" in grave you can wype the opponent's board.

You don't have to use Extra Deck cards that much, but these might be good in crucial moments and situations. In the side deck you can find even more good options that can work with the main deck if you want to try and build something better. I hope you liked it!
Main wincon is Rank 8 with Draglubion, with Gren Maju being a backup plan.

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Power-Ups
deck_description:
We're going to pop-pop-pop 'till we can't no more! 

This is a Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 purchase of the Structure Deck: Fire Kings. This will be a $10 upgrade consisting of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. 

Deckmaster: Crusadia Reclusia 
Domain Restrictions: FIRE / SPELLCASTER / CRUSADIA
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards from the SD: Fire Kings (in the sidedeck): 

  • ydke://QyWQBdgxXwEfqvUDtWTlAKyGqQMQjCYAE/00A2YlHAEi3xwEnCbOBTe5UQKx6sEFAK9nBf2JnAV6feQDcDZuA+OwKgPwlJoFONleAckOdgSEqkUCxTGKA3xJdwU8fZ4D+wR4AsEFUAKlTI8C+5oxAw==!bFjTA1YT1QGw3ugC!YzrEBalj9QNs2S4BIWoABMQAkQOdljgDwYheBP3sNQAF4zQDlVXOAF2xBQBhVmcD9esBBH8OEwAiSJkA!
  • https://ygoprodeck.com/pack/Structure%20Deck%3A%20Fire%20Kings/

Next, you will want to buy and add these cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://Tn8RBZ87JwRAAL8DvmF7AGWuwwFWdAkDDcWFBUgpmANYaEsDS/iKAIH8PwOpu6sBRfAuBWBpdgX1kzYFLfv+BNnChACJVxECgku5BQ31DAFudx0ExanaBJAGIwBEGfAACvc7A/32RAOVA4wAWXtjBN3RdwCnN4gBQKXzAKJPigA=!At+pADtpwAPdP+8DcU0qAEkllgBMa9gDlc48BYIDQgLTwNgCTMKSAJcdTgSNJ5gD!ietKAw==!

Notably, this deck does not use Infinite Impermanence which is currently a pricy card at $7. You may choose to add it into the deck or sell it to fund the $10 purchase of cards you'll need. 

Additional Resources can be found here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into 3 broad categories:

  • Big Monsters
  • Self-Revivers
  • Poppers

The Big Monsters:

- Beat over your opponents!
- Summons themselves from the Hand!

This categaory of monsters includes Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted , The Blazing Mars , and Burning Dragon in order to keep ourselves with a healthy board with monsters that are easy to summon from hand with their own effects. These monsters do also have effects that trigger and give us benefits. 

Cards like Spell Card "Soul Exchange" and Trade-In are included to derive additional benefits from these cards. 

The Self-Revivers

- Be sticky and hard to Boardwipe!
- Have no fear of being destroyed and sent to the GY!
- Always have material to access the Extra Deck with! 

Monsters such as Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames and Sacred Fire King Garunix are vital to our strategy by easily reviving themselves from the graveyard and providing benefits on summon. Our goal every game to to access these two as soon as possible. 

Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames interacts with our opponent on their turn by reviving hereself and removing one of their monsters, and on our own turn allows us to revive one of our monsters in the GY, which can trigger additional effects. 

Sacred Fire King Garunix can revive from GY and then can destroy a monster in our deck, most cases destroying cards like Fencing Fire Ferret which will then allow us to interact with our opponent. 

Combined, these sticky monsters allow us to have plays every turn of the game and be resiliant to boardwipes. 

To find Sacred Fire King Garunix we use Foolish Burial and Fire King Island with its searchers.

To summon the Link-3 Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames we use extenders such as Crusadia Arboria and our deckmaster Crusadia Reclusia 

Poppers

- Interact with our Opponent! 
- Remove their hopes and dreams!

The primary method this deck interacts is through popping cards using the deckmaster Crusadia Reclusia. Addtionally, Sacred Fire King Garunix will allow us to access other cards which destroy cards when they themselves are destroyed such as Fire King High Avatar Garunix and Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys 

We do not care ourselves if our monsters are destroyed, so we use cards such as Dark Hole, Supply Squad, and Ebon Sun to benefit from this aspect of the deck. 

What do we want our deckmaster to do?  Crusadia Reclusia 

- Free Extender! 
- Triggers Sacred Fire King Garunix!
- Reliable, Reuseable popping!
- Crusadia OTK!

The Crusadia Reclusia we choose as deckmaster has an inherent summon and a reliable pop of an opponent's card when we want it. Notably, this can destroy either a spell/trap or a monster, providing great flexiblity. 

 Additionally, it can provide access to the Crusadia Engine, a combo that puts out Crusadia Regulex with backup from Crusadia Revival to attack all monsters on the field with a amplified attack stat. This combo starts from normal summoning Crusadia Reclusia to link into Crusadia Magius then summoning Crusadia Reclusia using its own inherent summoning.  

To captilize on the popping effect, we use cards such as Enemy Controller to tribute Crusadia Reclusia before its own effect destroys it. Remember that the popping is optional, and we may choose to use Crusadia Reclusia as a simple extender to access our other Extra Deck Link Monsters. 

To recap:

Important Cards: Sacred Fire King Garunix , Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames , Supply Squad , Crusadia Reclusia 

Strategy Elevator Pitch: Pop all their stuff, then beat them up with high-level, high-attack monsters. 

Suggested Alternatives:

 Diabellstar the Black Witch + Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye + Susurrus of the Sinful Spoils , Battlin' Boxer Uppercutter , Salamangreat Gazelle + Salamangreat Miragestallio , Dogmatika Nexus , Infernoble Knight Captain Oliver , Fighting Flame Swordsman , Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians , Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax , Magical Dimension , Snake-Eye Ash , Magmacho Dragon , Ancient Warriors - Ambitious Cao De , Brushfire Knight , Successor Soul , The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode , Lava Golem , Volcanic Queen , Gold Pride - Nytro Head 

Please remember, the most important goal is to have fun!

deck_name: World Chalice - Spright and Diabellstar Engine
deck_description:
After the release of Ib (the World Chalice Justiciar), World Chalice has potential again.
It's relativiely simple in this build, no room for non-engine, but what we can run a total of 14 ways to get to out main starter, T.G. Rocket Salamander.
The base combo is this-
Summon Rocket Salamander (through any means, Normal summon, special summon through OSS or One for One, ect) > Tribute Salamander for it's effect, summon Screw Serpent, Serpent revive Salamander, Synchro into Ib, Ib effect add World Legacy World Chalice.
If you special summoned Salamander, you're fine to just normal summon the Chalice by tributing Ib. If you normal summoned Salamander, you'll need to summon Ib the the EMZ, and then link it off for Gravity Controller (after which you use Ib effect summon Crowned, link Crowned into Imduk, Tribute Controller and summon Chalice. then resume combo)
After summoning Chalice, use Ib's effect to summon Lee from deck, then Lee effect to add Crowned. Link Lee and Chalice into something (Currently testing Sprind, but Auram should work as well. This list was originally a Master Duel deck and I used Spright Elf, but that's banned in the TCG) then Chalice effect summon Guardragon and Crowned from deck. Next is where it changes up a bit, I know there's a lot you can do from this point but currently what I've found to work best is to XYZ into Gigantic and do Spright plays.
Currently Rocket Salamander (special summoned) gets me to Gigantic, S:P, Abomination, and Avramax OR Avramax (made with I:P), Earlie, Gigantic, and a set Sorrows
Originally in Master Duel, I would end on Apollousa instead of Abomination (Abomination is just a replacement with good arrows and an okay effect, I could see Saryuja Skull Dread being a good option as well)

merda

Who would've thought that this deck would be budget right now, with the most expensive card from the deck probably being kashtira fenrir lol.

Deck is very fun to play and surprisingly competetive (went 3-1 at locals and im a noob), most of the kashtira engine is used to xyz into arsenal falcon so you can just special ulcanix from the deck and go into your full fire king line into amblowhale. Kashtira birth is clutch against d shifter decks as well. The diabelstar is just there as an extra body and a ponix summon with the OG sinful spoils. If you can get either ulcanix or ponix effect off, it becomes very hard for your opponent. 

 

All the non engine you can just replace with whatever you like, for me this works because the droplet kinda gives you infinite chain blocks with kirin and the circle as well. You can choose to put more handtraps in the deck but the crossouts really help when going first. 

If you have things to recommend pls let me know!
